filteredListings.neighborhood_overview:
Bernal Heights is an urban village built onto a hill. As a result, it is one of the more magical neighborhoods of San Francisco. Walks in Bernal Heights include numerous stairway streets, hidden mini-parks and gardens, panoramic views of the city and the bay, and frequent opportunities for refreshment breaks at corner stores, cafes, restaurants and bars. This is an urban hiker’s paradise! To really get the full neighborhood experience you’ll have to take it off-roading since some areas are only accessible by foot, but even if you stick to streets you’ll still fall in love with the whimsical charm around every corner.

There are numerous coffee shops in the immediate vicinity, and the famous Mitchell's ice cream is just two blocks away. If you are craving a San Francisco burrito, Taqueria Can-Cun is just around the corner. filteredListings.neighborhood_overview:
We are conveniently located in NoPa near everything.

NoPa is a tiny section carved out of the larger Western Addition neighborhood. It’s named after its location, the streets sitting *north of the panhandle* (the narrow eastern strip of Golden Gate Park). It’s a trendy area with popular, highly rated bars and restaurants along Divisadero Street, its eastern border, and rising costs because of its prime central location within the city. You’ll also find college students in the area, as the University of San Francisco makes up the neighborhood’s western border.

NoPa offers great little cafes and shops within 2 blocks and along the Divisadero corridor 4 blocks away. You can walk to Haight/Ashbury, Golden Gate Park, UCSF and Alamo Square and its famous painted ladies; the Castro, Mission, downtown, Union Square, Pac Heights and the Marina using public transportation.

There are colorful murals around the neighborhoods. Casual Mexican and Asian food spots dot the streets, along with diners, corner stores, and ethnic markets.

Outer Mission borders Excelsior District which is home to the Excelsior Festival, an annual event celebrating its cultural diversity. It brings in about 5,000 people each year and has free music and entertainment. There is also Jerry Day, a celebration of the area’s most famous former resident, Jerry Garcia, lead singer of the Grateful Dead.

filteredListings.host_about:
Greetings from Noelle and George!

We both grew up in the Bay Area and are college sweethearts having both majored in biological sciences. We chose to live and raise a family which includes our three children in San Francisco because of the beautiful landscape, amazing culture and diversity, priceless climate and lets not forget exploring this beautiful city through the iconic cable car rides.

As a family we enjoy spending most of our time outdoors which includes hiking in the Marin Headlands, breezy walks along Ocean Beach, as well as biking in Golden Gate Park to name a few. Camping is a major part of our summer routine in Lake Tahoe, Yosemite National Park, and Camp Mendocino. We also enjoy Lake Tahoe during the winter months for skiing and snowboarding. Noelle and I are also avid sports fans and LOVE attending San Francisco Giants, Oakland Athletics, Golden State Warriors, San Francisco Forty Niners, Oakland Raiders and San Jose Shark games with our children and friends. Our weekends are also consumed with youth sports as our children play on baseball, basketball, golf, and swimming teams.

 We are lucky enough to live in an area which embraces the arts and we are just a short stroll away from the many music festivals which San Francisco has to offer and a few of our favorite events to attend are the Blue Grass Festival and Outside Lands both in Golden Gate Park. 

San Francisco offers a variety of multi-cultural cuisine all within a short distance from each other whether it be a walk, drive or door step away. Some of our favorites include, fresh seafood, Pho, Mission-style burritos, Korean BBQ, Cioppino, or exploring our palates with tasting world renowned wine and cheese at the Ferry Building!

Fillmore Street has dozens of restaurants, clothing and furniture stores. And, of course, the legendary jazz district and the famed Fillmore Auditorium music venue, plus the Sundance Cinema movie complex.

A smaller, neighborhood movie theater is just two blocks from the flat, on Sacramento Street. There is an eclectic mix of shops and restaurants along Sacramento Street.

Popular restaurants just a short stroll from our home include Eliza's (Chinese), Bistro SF Grill (gourmet burgers), Curbside Cafe (French Bistro), Sift (dessert cafe) and Osteria (Northern Italian).
